En Passant: An Analysis of Trends and Patterns in Chess¶

Chess is one of the most popular board games. It is played on many levels: here in the Philippines, we can commonly see people playing Chess with each other on the street, yet international tournaments are held as well and Chess champions and grandmasters enjoy relatively widespread fame.

Chessgames.com is an internet site dedicated to Chess. On the chessgames site we can find game, tournament, and player data among other things such as Chess openings and the like.

Problem¶

How has the Chess tournament scene been affected by time? Has it been decreasing? Increasing? Are there dips or peaks?

Do Chess players move randomly or are there similarities or patterns in how Chess players play? If there are patterns, how can we interpret them and which patterns are the most successful? Knowing these will allow Chess players (aspiring Chess champions) to know which patterns to practice and emulate.

Section 1. Executive Summary¶

For chess games enthusiasts, it is their desire to become good chess players and to be ranked among the best in this tournament. What better way to improve their skills by learning from the worlds best? This report will provide information on proven winning strategy played in this game by the best chess players around the world. This information should help aspiring players to hone their skills and to show that they have what it takes to become champions in the game of chess.

Chess games information were retrieved from the website, Chessgames.com. It has an online database which contains records of chess games played around the world since 1843 and information about world known chess game players. It is also a community with a discussion forum where members can discuss anything about chess. Web scraping using Pythons library BeautifulSoup was used to gather data from the website.

Records of chess games that have taken place since 1843 up to 2019 were retrieved from the website. Information on when and where the game was played, who won and how fast the game was won are all part of the records. From the records, the increase popularity of the game is evident with the increasing number of tournaments being played year on year around the world. Perhaps not surprisingly, records show that player on the White Side wins more times that the player on the Black Side. More so, it can take as few as 1 move to win the game to as most as 228 moves. Champions-wannabee might want to look at how the 1-move games were won.

Player information was also retrieved which includes their FIDE-rating and the number of game played. FIDE which stands for Fdration Internationale Des checs is the governing body for international chess competitions. This information showed that there is a correlation with the number of games played with the higher FIDE-rating. Chess game enthusiasts should become followers of and should learn from players with higher FIDE-rating.

The opening moves taken by the players from about 900,000+ chess games were also analyzed. From 20 possible first moves, the move that is most taken by the white player is the pawn moving to E4. This was the first move in 47% of all the games. Further, 38% of the games with this first move were won. The heat maps of the most common first move by both White player and the success of the corresponding game are shown on the report. These are guides to chess players on how to start a game with a high level of probability of winning the game.

Lastly, the discussion forum was reviewed with the objective of learning what are the topics of interest discussed by the members of the site. This information can help interested individuals in using the right keywords to search the forum for tips and techniques that can help them in their journey to become better chess players.

Retrieving the Scraped Data from the SQLite Database¶

We retrieve the contents of our SQLite database tournaments_1843_to_2019.db

In [3]:
conn = sqlite3.connect(db_data_path)
c = conn.cursor()

# Retrieve tournament games
df_tourn_games = pd.DataFrame(c.execute(
    """
SELECT * FROM games
""").fetchall(),
    columns=['event_locale', 'game', 'moves', 'opening', 'result', 'year'])
df_tourn_games = df_tourn_games.drop_duplicates()
df_tourn_games['year'] = df_tourn_games['year'].astype('int64')
df_tourn_games['moves'] = df_tourn_games['moves'].astype('int64')

# Retrieve player data
df_players = pd.DataFrame(c.execute(
    """
SELECT * FROM players
""").fetchall(), columns=['fide', 'name', 'games', 'start_year', 'end_year'])
# df_players['fide'] = df_players['fide'].astype('int64')
df_players['start_year'] = df_players['start_year'].astype('int64')
df_players['end_year'] = df_players['end_year'].astype('int64')

# Retrieve opening squares
df_explorer = pd.DataFrame(c.execute(
    """
SELECT * FROM first_move
""").fetchall())
df_explorer.columns = ['move', 'games', 'order', 'white', 'black', 'draw']

# Retrieve chessforums forums
df_texts = pd.DataFrame(c.execute(
    """
SELECT * FROM texts
""").fetchall())
df_texts.columns = ['name', 'text']

# Retrieve ECO opening codes
df_eco = pd.DataFrame(c.execute(
    """
SELECT * FROM eco_codes
""").fetchall())
df_eco.columns = ['eco_code', 'title']
df_eco = df_eco.set_index('eco_code')['title']

We have 7 columns:

  • event_locale - the tournament name or the location of the game
  • game - game number in the tournament and the two players, White vs. Black
  • moves - number of moves in the game; note that one move consists of white's move and black's move
  • opening - name of the opening move set
  • result
    • White Win [1-0]
    • Black Win [0-1]
    • Draw [1/2-1/2]
  • year
  • opening_code - a code designating which opening move set was used, according to the Encyclopedia of Chess Openings (ECO)

df1_openings_wins = df1.groupby(
    ['opening_code', 'result']).size().unstack().drop(index='000')

opening_totals = list(df1_openings_wins.apply(lambda x: x.sum(), axis=1))
df1_openings_wins = df1_openings_wins.apply(lambda x: x/x.sum(), axis=1)

Section 4. Story¶

Based on what we can glean from the chessgames website, what are the trends in chess over the years?

Number of Games¶

We noticed earlier that although the number of chess tournament games had generally been increasing over time, there were periods which saw declines. Let's plot the number of games per year, from 1843 to 2019.

The number of games (y-axis) will be represented as a logarithmic scale to mitigate the effect of the balloon in the number of games recently.

Here we plot the Number of Tournament Games Played per Year vs. the Number of Tournament Games Played for that year.

In [21]:
df1_games = df1.groupby('year')['game'].count()

fig, ax = plt.subplots(1, 1, figsize=(15, 8))
ax = df1_games.plot(color='darkorange')
ax.set_xlabel('Year')
ax.set_ylabel('Number of Tournament Games Played')
ax.set_title('Number of Tournament Games Played per Year')
ax.set_yscale('log')
plt.show()

ANALYSIS¶

There is a generally increasing trend in the number of tournament games per year, but we notice several dips in the 1890s, from 1915-1919, from 1941-1945, and in the 1980s. The dip in 2019 is because the year is not finished yet.

We cannot explain the dips in the 1890s and 1980s, but it is likely that the dips in 1915-1919 and 1941-1945 are connected to World War I and II, respectively.

It is good to see that there has been an exponential increase in the number of chess tournaments starting approximately in the 1990s. This increase is so pronounced that we had to plot the above chart on a semilogarithmic scale. On the other hand, this may be because chess games and tournaments are better documented in recent times due to improved technological capability.

Winning Percentage by Side¶

In the tournament DataFrame, df_tourn_games, there is a column named result, containing the outcome of each game.

The possible outcomes are as follows:

  • 1-0 : White Victory
  • 0-1 : Black Victory
  • - : Draw

This cell will show the number of games won by White, Black, or a Draw, and the winning percentage of each.

In [22]:
result_dict = {'1-0': 'White', '0-1': 'Black', '-': 'Draw', 
               'total': 'total'}
color_dict = {'White': 'blanchedalmond',
              'Draw': 'lightgray', 'Black': 'saddlebrown'}
df1_bw = df1.groupby('result')['game'].count().sort_values(ascending=True)
df1_bw.index = [result_dict[result] for result in df1_bw.index]
fig, ax = plt.subplots(1, 1, figsize=(12, 8))
ax = df1_bw.plot.barh(color=[color_dict[color] for color in df1_bw.index])
ax.set_title('Games Won by Side')
ax.set_xlabel('Games Won')
ax.set_ylabel('Side')
for i, v in enumerate(df1_bw.values):
    ax.text(v/2, i-0.05, (str(v)+' ({:.02f}%)'.format(
        100*v/sum(df1_bw.values))), color='k', fontweight='bold', 
            fontsize=int(v/3000))
plt.show()

ANALYSIS¶

White has an undeniable advantage over Black.

Despite being ahead by only half a move, White is able to take offense immediately, and thus Black is often forced into defense very early on.

Number of Moves¶

How has the number of moves in chess tournament games changed over the years?

The following cell groups the number of moves by year and averages them, to get the mean number of moves for all games in a year.

In [23]:
df1_moves = df1.groupby('year')['moves'].mean()

fig, ax = plt.subplots(1, 1, figsize=(15, 8))
ax = df1_moves.plot(color='darkorange')
ax.set_xlabel('Year')
ax.set_ylabel('Average Number of Moves')
ax.set_title('Average Number of Moves Played in Tournament Games, per Year')
ax.set_yscale('log')
plt.show()

ANALYSIS¶

Over time, there does not seem to be a general trend in the number of moves. It is relatively stable at around 40-45.

It may be noticed that the number of moves occasionally fluctuates abnormally high or low. The reason for this is likely because these spikes tend to coincide with the slumps (dips) in the number of games per year. In these cases, the mean becomes more sensitive to outliers. Thus, nothing can be concluded.

Nevertheless, it is interesting to note that some of the highest spikes coincide with the two World Wars (1917 and 1943).

Opening Moveset¶

"Opening", or "Opening moves", is a term used to refer to the first few moves in a chess game. The opening chosen will depend much on the personal skill, style, and preference of the player, and its success will also depend on how well the opponent defends against it. Through the years, some openings have been developed, tried, tested, and extensively studied. The following chart shows the Top 10 openings from 1843 to 2019.

This cell re-plots the Top 10 Chess Opening Moveset.

    ax.text(v+100, i-0.17, str(v), color='k', fontweight='bold', fontsize=14)

ANALYSIS¶

Some Chess Openings are frequently used, likely because of their effectiveness or simply because of popularity. Using a less-popular opening might be less effective, but also might catch an opponent by surprise.

Chess Notation¶

According to 'https://www.dummies.com/games/chess/understanding-chess-notation/':

Many kinds of chess notation exist, from forsythe (a notation that computers understand) to different notations for various languages. One kind of notation, however, is universally understood: algebraic, which uses a single letter and number to name each square and a letter for each chess piece. This notation system replaced the older English descriptive notation which used an abbreviated form of a verbal description of the moves because chess is for all people, not just English-speaking people.

The numbering and lettering of the chess board is oriented to the white players position and looks like this:

White at bottom, Black at top.

The 'Chess Opening Explorer' page on the chessgames site allows users to explore different possible starting combinations of moves. However, exploring deep (more number of moves) requires their premium subscription, and thus we will only analyze the very first move of White.

The following code creates several DataFrames that will allow us to plot the frequency of opening squares into a heatmap.

In [27]:
df_exp_trunc = df_explorer.copy()
df_exp_trunc['move'] = df_explorer['move'].apply(lambda x: x[-2:])
df_exp_trunc['col'] = df_exp_trunc['move'].apply(lambda x: x[0])
df_exp_trunc['row'] = df_exp_trunc['move'].apply(
    lambda x: x[1]).astype('int64')

df_board = pd.DataFrame(columns=list(
    string.ascii_lowercase[:8]), index=range(1, 9)).fillna(0)
df_whites = pd.DataFrame(columns=list(
    string.ascii_lowercase[:8]), index=range(1, 9)).fillna(0)
df_blacks = pd.DataFrame(columns=list(
    string.ascii_lowercase[:8]), index=range(1, 9)).fillna(0)

for idx in df_exp_trunc.index:
    row = df_exp_trunc['row'][idx]
    col = df_exp_trunc['col'][idx]
    df_board.loc[row, col] += df_exp_trunc['games'][idx]
    df_whites.loc[row, col] += (df_exp_trunc['white']
                                [idx]*df_exp_trunc['games'][idx])
    df_blacks.loc[row, col] += (df_exp_trunc['black']
                                [idx]*df_exp_trunc['games'][idx])

df_board.fillna(0, inplace=True)
df_whites = (df_whites / df_board).fillna(0)
df_blacks = (df_blacks / df_board).fillna(0)
df_blacks.fillna(0, inplace=True)
df_board = df_board.astype('int64')

What Squares Does White Play?¶

White has a total of 16 squares that it may play at the beginning; eight pawns may move either one or two steps forward, or the knights have two possible moves each, making for 20 possible starting moves. Which squares are most often played by White?

White can play all 16 squares but tends to play only a few squares very frequently, thus making for an uninformative heatmap. To attempt to remedy this, let us plot frequency on a logarithmic scale instead.

This code plots the frequency of openings squares used by White on a heatmap. The logarithms of the frequencies have been taken.

In [28]:

    np.log(df_board.sort_index(ascending=False)).replace(-np.inf, np.nan)
    .fillna(0), cmap='Reds', square=True, annot=True, annot_kws={"size": 18},
    linewidths=1, linecolor='k')
ax.set_title('log(Frequency) of Opening Squares used by White')

plt.show()

ANALYSIS¶

White almost always plays e4 and d4; the middle two pawns moving two squares forward. These moves allow early mobility for the queen and/or the bishops.

Black has the highest percentage of winning given White plays h4. This information is significantly less useful to Black than it is to White.

Player Ratings¶

According to Wikipedia,

A player's Elo rating is represented by a number which increases or decreases depending on the outcome of games between rated players. After every game, the winning player takes points from the losing one. The difference between the ratings of the winner and loser determines the total number of points gained or lost after a game. In a series of games between a high-rated player and a low-rated player, the high-rated player is expected to score more wins. If the high-rated player wins, then only a few rating points will be taken from the low-rated player. However, if the lower-rated player scores an upset win, many rating points will be transferred. The lower-rated player will also gain a few points from the higher rated player in the event of a draw. This means that this rating system is self-correcting.

Several organizations keep their own Elo ratings of chess players, including the Fdration Internationale des checs or World Chess Federation (FIDE).

In general, how do players' FIDE ratings fare as they play more and more games?

Let's try plotting the highest FIDE rating achieved against the total number of games played. Each point represents one player.

In [31]:
fig, ax = plt.subplots(1, 1, figsize=(15, 9))
ax.plot(df2['games'], df2['fide'], 'c.', ms=10,
        mew=0.5, mec='Blue', label='Data')
ax.set_title("Highest FIDE Rating vs. Number of Games Played", fontsize=20)
ax.set_xlabel('Number of Games Played')
ax.set_ylabel('Highest FIDE Rating Achieved')
plt.show()

ANALYSIS¶

Looks like either an exponential relationship or a power law! This makes sense because players with lower ratings should be able to climb faster, because they are awarded more points for winning a match. As the above-mentioned article continues,

Players whose ratings are too low should, in the long run, do better than the rating system predicts and thus gain rating points until the ratings reflect their true playing strength.

Thus, if one simply want to attain a respectable FIDE rating, then they need not play very many games, but if one wants to achieve a very high FIDE rating, then one should play a disproportionate number of games.

Re-plotting the same as above, but using a logarithmic scale.

In [32]:
fig, ax = plt.subplots(1, 1, figsize=(15, 9))
ax.plot(df2['games'], df2['fide'], 'c.', ms=10,
        mew=0.5, mec='Blue', label='Data')
ax.set_xscale('log')
ax.set_yscale('log')
ax.set_title(
    "Highest FIDE Rating vs. Number of Games Played (log)", fontsize=20)
ax.set_xlabel('Number of Games Played')
ax.set_ylabel('Highest FIDE Rating Achieved')
plt.show()

The trend is starting to become apparent. To finish this analysis, let's fit the points to a power law.

The following code defines a power law function, and fits the data points to the function using lmfit. The data points are plotted (scatter), the initial guess is the black dashed line, and the final 'best' fit is plotted as a solid red line.

In [33]:
def power(x, A, alpha):
    return A * x ** (-alpha)


df2_games_fide = df2[['games', 'fide']].copy().dropna()

x = np.array(df2_games_fide['games'])
y = np.array(df2_games_fide['fide'])
y, x = sorter(y, x)

power_model = Model(power)
results_power = power_model.fit(y, x=x, A=1927, alpha=-0.05)
# print(results_power.fit_report())

plt.figure(figsize=(15, 9))

plt.loglog(x, y, 'co', ms=6, mew=0.5, mec='Blue', label="Data")
plt.loglog(x, results_power.init_fit, 'k--', label="Initial Fit")
plt.loglog(x, results_power.best_fit, 'r-', lw=3, label="Best Fit")
plt.xlabel('Number of Games Played')
plt.ylabel('Highest FIDE Rating Achieved')
plt.title(
    "Power Law Fitting of Highest FIDE Rating vs. Number of Games Played", 
    fontsize=20)
plt.legend(loc='upper left', fontsize=14)
plt.grid()
plt.tick_params(labelsize=14)

plt.show()

ANALYSIS¶

Playing more and more games sees diminishing marginal returns on the FIDE rating.

However, it is notable to observe that the lower right portion of the graph is blank, meaning that although people who played a low number of games could get high FIDE ratings straight away, no one who played a high number of games remained with a low FIDE rating.

Thus, the best way to increase FIDE rating is still to play more games.

def create_word_cloud(string):
    mask = np.array(Image.open('figures/pawn.png'))
    cloud = WordCloud(background_color="white", max_words=100,
                      mask=mask, stopwords=set(STOPWORDS))
    cloud.generate(string)

Section 5. Conclusion and Closing¶

With more tournaments being held, there are more opportunities for enthusiasts to display their prowess in the game of chess. Further, it is only through playing (and winning) in more chess tournaments that a player will improve his or her FIDE-rating.

As mentioned from the start of the report, learning from the experts is the best way for enthusiasts to hone their chess playing skills. These experts have played so many times and in the process have tested (or done) so many moves that they could have defined the best strategy to follow in order to win the game. As a learner, you avoid the process of trial and error by learning the experts strategy. From the information in this report, we recommend that you follow the following top 10 players in this sport (based on highest FIDE Rating).

  • CARLSEN, Magnus
  • KASPAROV, Garry
  • CARUANA, Fabiano
  • ARONIAN, Levon
  • SO, Wesley
  • VACHIER-LAGRAVE, Maxime
  • ANAND, Viswanathan
  • KRAMNIK, Vladimir
  • TOPALOV, Veselin
  • NAKAMURA, Hikaru

From the analysis of the first/opening moves, enthusiasts will have the idea on how to start their games. However, this is just the first of the so many other moves to complete the game. Therefore, players should not just stop at learning the best first moves, but should also learn on what the succeeding moves should be, particularly in response to the opponents move. Nevertheless, having a good first move provides a one-move advantage already and a good confidence level to start the game.

Lastly, there are discussion forums available in the internet where enthusiasts can follow discussions or ask questions regarding the game of chess. These forums have members from around the globe who have various levels of expertise. There is a good chance that somebody might have been in the same situation that you are and that he or she may have already dealt with the situation or may have the right next steps to move forward to complete and to win the game.

Enjoy the game!
